7. Operational Protocols

7.1 The Golden Bridge Protocol: Dynamically Derived Cooling Periods

When GNSI(t) < GNSI_warning, the system triggers a cooling period of duration:

T_cool = T_base · (GNSI_normal - GNSI(t)) / (GNSI_normal - GNSI_critical)

Where:

· T_base is a base cooling period (e.g., 15 minutes, derived from historical crisis escalation times)
· GNSI_normal is the average GNSI during peacetime
· GNSI_critical is the GNSI value at which escalation probability > 0.5 (derived from historical calibration)

During T_cool:

· All autonomous offensive systems enter standby mode
· No new targeting data is accepted without human verification
· A dedicated crisis communication channel opens between all parties

False Positive Analysis: The expected cost of false positives is:

E[cost_false] = P(false positive) · C_cooling

Where C_cooling is the operational cost of a cooling period. This must be balanced against:

E[cost_true] = P(missed detection) · C_escalation

Where C_escalation is the cost of nuclear escalation. Given the astronomical asymmetry (C_escalation >> C_cooling), even relatively high false positive rates are acceptable.

7.2 Shared Reality Ledger

A permissioned blockchain maintained by neutral nations (e.g., Switzerland, Sweden, Brazil, South Africa) records all "Confirmed Events"—incidents verified by at least two independent sources with cryptographic attestation.

Consensus Rule: An event is added to the ledger iff:

|{ i : verify(i, event) = True }| ≥ ⌈2N_neutral/3⌉

Where N_neutral is the number of neutral validator nations.

This prevents any single actor from unilaterally declaring a false‑flag event as "confirmed."

